description: From Ancient Greek ψυχικός (psukhikós)  +‎ -al; comparable to a surface analysis of psyche +‎ -ical.

entries.meaning: Performed by or pertaining to the psyche (the mind, spirit, or both): mental, psychic. [from 17th c.]
examples: Who could say where the fleshly impulse ceased, or the psychical impulse began?

entries.meaning: (theology) Pertaining to the animal nature of man, as opposed to the spirit. [from 18th c.]
Outside the realm of the physical; supernatural, psychic. [from 19th c.]
